In article <C137lK5QQtJH072yn@crl.com> lchiu@crl.com (Laurence Chiu) writes:

[Snip]

  Am I supposed to know the real number of
>cylinders this drive has, input this while enabling LBA mode and
>then reformat?

Yes...infact if you have a BIOS that supports LBA, then that BIOS probably 
does auto detection of the drive.  Look at that and use that information (if 
you do not have the CHS info of the drive).  Then, in the mode section, select 
LBA.  You will see that the original number of cylinder get halved and the 
number of heads are doubled while the total number of sectors stays constant.  
Once that is done, you can run FDISK from the boot floppy and reformat your 
drive.  Make sure to activate the boot partition.

Good luck.

